## Borders of plates
### Types of plate boundaries
![Pasted image 20220906130209.png|200](data:image/png;base64,)


#### ***Divergent <-|->***
- Where plates are moving away from eachother
	- Causes large amounts of tensions
		- Earthquakes, fractured layers of rock
- AKA spreading center, rift valley, mid-ocean ridges
- Majority of them are underwater
	- Where new seafloor forms
		- The thinnest crust on Earth
	- Mid-ocean ridges and Terrestrial rift valleys ^0d08d0
- Partial melting occurs from below, forming new rock
- Most common site of [[Unsorted/Volcanism\|Volcanism]], because the crust is thinnest there
	- But th eeruptions are relatively mild
	- Almost always basaltic [[Unsorted/Volcanism#Effusive Eruptions\|Effusive eruptions]]
- Formation
	  1. Starts on continental crust, above rising magma
	  2. Rift velley forms, very fractured canyon
	  3. Narrow seaway develops
		  1. The red sea is a submerged rift valley
		  2. Likely to form large ocean one day
	  4. Ocean basin develops and grows
		  1. Boundary becomes a mid-ocean ridge
	- ![Pasted image 20220906130306.png|200](data:image/png;base64,)
#### ***Convergent ->|<-***
- Where 2 plates are colliding
- Can cause subduction
	- Oceanic plates travel under continental plates and meltConverg
- Cause the deadliest earthquakes
	- And the most [[Unsorted/Volcanism#Explosive Eruptions\|Explosive Eruptions]]
- 3 subtypes
	- **Oceanic-oceanic convergence**
		- 2 Ocean plates collide
		- The older plate will subduct because it's denser
			- Had more time to cool
		- Water-saturated crust has exotic interactions with upper mantle
			- Causes [[Unsorted/Volcanism#Island arcs\|Volcanism#Island arcs]] above where the subducting plate begins to melt
			- Known as partial melting
			- Always forms in an arc shape, because any plane intersecting a sphere creates an arc
				- Note: Earth's spherical shape causes much more plate-territory-conflict than a flat crust would
	- **Oceanic-continental convergence**
		-] Oceanic crust is denser than continental, so it's the one that subducts
			- Form volcanic arcs on land - **continental volcanic arcs**
			- Tends to form large mountain ranges, *some distance from the subduction zone*
		- Creates a deep-ocean trench where the oceanic plate gets subducted 
	- **Continental-continental convergence**
		- Always start with oceanic-continental convergence
		- When an oceanic plate is completely consumed by subduction, it'll force material upwards
			- Cannot go down, continental crust isn't dense enough to subduct
#### Transform ⇄
- Where 2 plates are sliding past eachother
	- Lots of friction from shearing forces
- Much less common, only 20%
	- Typically forms as little subfractures of divergent plate boundaries
- EG San Andreas Fault



#### Composite boundaries
- Oceanic divergent plate boundaries are fractured into many fractured strips
	- Transform plate boundaries happen along these fractures

## Lecture questions
- What is the continental drift?
- What is the evidence Wegener used to support the continental drift hypothesis
- How did the theory of plate tectonics
	- The idea that the continents fit together like puzzle pieces
	- Led to Alfred Wegener developing the continental drift hypothesis

### Causes
- Mantle convection
- ![Pasted image 20220906140145.png|200](data:image/png;base64,)
- 2 Forces
	- Slab pull
		- Occurs at convergent plate boundaries
		- Subducting oceanic plates direct mantle currents
		- Contributes much more to the extrusion of new oceanic crust than ridge push
	- Ridge push
		- Force caused by plates being pushed away from eachother at divergent boundaries
- ![1280px-Oceanic_spreading.svg.png|200](data:image/png;base64,)


## Evidence

1. Seafloor spreading
	1. Age of the seafloor, youngest at the center, older near continents
2. [[Unsorted/The Mantle#Hot spots and mantle plumes\|The Mantle#Hot spots and mantle plumes]]
	1. Seems shaky as evidence
		1. ***How do we know for sure that they don't move?***
3. Apparent polar wandering
	1. Magnetic north pole moves around DRASTICALLY over 100Ms of years (IE to equatorial regions)
	2. Long term changes more likely due to continental movement than magnetic alignment change or pole reversal
	3. Magnetic pole reversals
		1. Are evident due to repeated patterns of reversing polarity in oceanic crust
		2. Perhaps because rocks form slightly differently depending on direction of magnetic field?
4. Continents fit together
	1. Particularly when studied several hundred meters out to sea
5. Paleoclimates: Evidence of glaciers with similar rock composition spread across now-far-separated regions
6. Fossil evidence
	1. 

## History
- Originated from the idea that the continents fit together like puzzle pieces
	- Led to Alfred Wegener developing the continental drift hypothesis
	- Later refined in the 1870s
		- Found that the continental fit was much better when the surface ~200m out into the ocean was examined
		- Discovery that the Appalacian Mountains, British Isles,, Caledonian mountains used to be part of one range
			- They're millions of years older than the rockies, more erosion
			- ![Pasted image 20220901131126.png](data:image/png;base64,)
		- 3rd piece of evidence comes from Paleoclimates
			- Glacial till: Poorly mixed rock unit/layers
				- Boulders, rocks, pebbles, dust
				- Created by glaciers
					- They pick up rocks of all sizes along their path
					- When the glacier melts (usually around ocean), all rocks of various sizes are deposited
			- Glacial striations
				- Rocks being carried by glaciers scratched the ground as glaciers moved
			- Wagner discovered that they match between multiple continents
				- Southern America, Africa, India, and Australia
				- India is very hot, so the presence of glacial remnants is surprising
					- Explanations:
						- Everything was very cold at one point
						- India was further south at one point
			- North America has many tropical fossils and coal deposits
				- Likely a much swampier, equatorial region at one point
				- Meanwhile South America showed evidence of glaciers, while in modern day it is a jungle
			- Fossil evidence
				- *Fossils of plants and land animals*
				- Found all across the world
					- *Very* unlikely that they could cross the ocean naturally, so it suggested the continents were at one point adjacent

- 1940s: Mapping of the ocean floor during WWII to study submarine camoflauge led to more understanding of oceanic continental boundaries
	- Such as mid-ocean ridges
		- Comparable to rift-valleys on land
		- ![pt7-mid-ocean-ridge-noaa-3483089670.jpg|200](data:image/png;base64,)
- 1960s: Using radioactive dating let us understand the age of different regions of the ocean floor
	- No place on the sea floor is older than 180 million years
	- ![th-2289059806.jpg|200](data:image/png;base64,)
- 1950s: Development of the global seismograhic network
	- Used to detect nuclear tests based on earthquakes caused by them
	- Revealed that nearly all earthquakes happen at plate boundaries
- Marie Tharp (woman) combined seismographic and bathymetric data to create the theory of plate tectonics
	- Credit was stolen by Heezen
